revision.text:
{{other uses|Aghazadeh (disambiguation)}} '''''Aghazadeh''''' ({{lang-fa|آقازاده|lit=born to ''[[Agha (title)|Agha]]'' or [[Nobility|noble]]-born}})<ref>{{citation|url=http://iranpulse.al-monitor.com/index.php/2012/09/376/ahmadinejads-last-visit-to-new-york/|title=Rafsanjani reacts to his Son’s Arrest; Ahmadinejad’s Last Visit to New York|author=Eskandar Sadeghi-Boroujerdi|date=25 September 2012|access-date=15 July 2017|work=Al-Monitor}}</ref> is a term that entered the [[colloquialism]] in [[Iran]] in the 1990s<ref>{{citebook|author=Barry Rubin|title=The Middle East: A Guide to Politics, Economics, Society and Culture|publisher=Routledge|year=2015|isbn=9781317455783|entry=Blocked Postwar Recovery|page=199}}</ref> to describe the children of [[elite]] who emerge as the men of means and influence, usually in a way that resembles familial [[nepotism]] and [[corruption]].<ref name="SM">{{cite book|author=Suzanne Maloney|title=Iran's Political Economy since the Revolution|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521738149|page=239}}</ref> This includes utilization of the positions within the hierarchy to gain [[inside information]] and [[Economic rent|preferential]] status which results in replication of wealth and power across generations<ref name="SM"/> and means "fewer top positions are available to talented people without family connections".<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/ill-official-highlights-concentration-of-power-in-iran|author=Mehdi Khalaji|title=Ailing Official Highlights Concentration of Power in Iran|date=11 June 2014|access-date=15 July 2017|type=Policy Alert|work=The Washington Institute for Near East Policy}}</ref>
The phenomenon is exemplified with family members of high-ranking officials such as [[Hashemi Rafsanjani]], [[Ali Akbar Nategh-Nouri|Nategh Nouri]] and [[Abbas Vaez-Tabasi|Vaez Tabasi]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Suzanne Maloney|title=Iran's Political Economy since the Revolution|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521738149|page=240}}</ref>
In 2017, "good genes" ({{lang-fa|ژن خوب}}), a new term was coined and became synonymous with ''Aghazadeh''s and "the [[Privilege (social inequality)|privileges]] they enjoy".<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/iran-aref-son-good-genes-firestorm/28718364.html|title=Firestorm In Iran As Politician's Son Credits 'Good Genes' For His Success|date=5 September 2017|access-date=5 September 2017|author=Golnaz Esfandiari|work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty}}</ref> == References == {{reflist}} [[Category:Persian words and phrases]] [[Category:Pejoratives]] [[Category:Political terminology of Iran]] [[Category:Corruption in Iran]] [[Category:Nepotism]] [[Category:Words coined in the 1990s]] {{Iran-culture-stub}}

