{{main|Simplified Chinese characters}}
A relatively small number of [[Chinese characters]] known as {{zh-hans}}: {{lang|zh|简繁一对多}}; {{zh-hant}}: {{lang|zh|簡繁一對多}} do not have a one-to-one mapping between their [[Simplified Chinese|simplified]] and [[Traditional Chinese|traditional]] forms. 

This is usually because the simplification process merged two or more distinct characters into one. In most cases, these traditional characters are [[homonym]]s, having the same pronunciation but different meanings. As a result, converting text from simplified to traditional characters is difficult to automate, especially in the case of common characters such as {{fontcolor||#FFD0D0|后}}[[File:Cmbox move.png|10px|⇄|link=]]{{fontcolor||#DFDFFF|後后}} ("behind" or "[[empress]]"), {{fontcolor||#FFD0D0|表}}[[File:Cmbox move.png|10px|⇄|link=]]{{fontcolor||#DFDFFF|表錶}} (table, clock), {{fontcolor||#FFD0D0|奸}}[[File:Cmbox move.png|10px|⇄|link=]]{{fontcolor||#DFDFFF|奸姦}} ("[[traitor]]" or "[[rape]]") and more.

In a much smaller number of cases, a single traditional character is mapped to multiple simplified characters.

The following is an exhaustive list of all characters whose simplified and traditional forms do not map in a one-to-one manner. Simplified characters are marked with a {{fontcolor||#FFD0D0|pink}} background, and traditional characters with  {{fontcolor||#DFDFFF|light blue}}.

